Tingko: Miss Jiyanama, you... How long will it be before you start talking to us again?
Tingko: It doesn't matter how you treat me, but you can't do this to the princess...
Jiyanama: ...My apologies. Princess, please eat.
Tindoiimu: ...Thank you, Jiyanama.
Tindoiimu: .........
Tingko: Um? Why aren't you eating, princess?
Tingko: Jiyanama, this food is completely raw!
Tingko: How could you give this to the princess!?
Jiyanama: The princess doesn't wish to eat it?
Tingko: Of course she can't eat it!
Jiyanama: The Qilin Tribe allocates a certain amount of food to us each month. If I have to remake it, the princess will go hungry tomorrow.
Tingko: You...! Are you threatening the princess!?
Tindoiimu: Forget it. I can still eat the vegetables. They don't need to be cooked.
Tingko: Princess! How can you...
Tindoiimu: It's fine. No harm done.
Tindoiimu: I'm sure all this cooking is tiring, Jiyanama. Why not head back to your room and rest?
Jiyanama: ......
Tingko: I know that Jiyanama is upset, but...
Tingko: ...she can't take it out on you, Tindy. She's your nanny, but that doesn't mean she can give you an attitude...
Tindoiimu: Her eyes were swollen. She must be thinking about Faayida again.
Tingko: But that wasn't your fault...!
Tindoiimu: If blaming me makes it any easier for her, then let her blame me.
Tingko: But... you're innocent!
Tindoiimu: Innocent how? A tribe member is dead. I am part of all this, too. I don't have the right to be innocent.
Tingko: Princess...
Juan Yun: Hello~ Sorry to roll up while you're eating.
Tingko: Lord Juan Yun, you again...
Juan Yun: And hello to you too, Tingko. I've come to chat with the princess.
Juan Yun: Princess, you look─
Tindoiimu: If you have come here to ask me if I will act as shaman for the Peace Ceremony,
Tindoiimu: my answer is the same as it was yesterday, the day before, and the day before that. I won't do it.
Juan Yun: I see... It's a shame you haven't changed your mind yet...
Tindoiimu: I am a hostage, not a guest. I am not suited to serve as the wind shaman.
Tindoiimu: I hope that my lord will not continue to put me in this position.
Juan Yun: Why, princess? If it is because of what occurred at the Metamorphosis, it is even more important now that you serve as shaman.
Juan Yun: To educate more beasts about you and the Insect Tribe. This will bring about greater understanding, and things will gradually improve.
Tindoiimu: (Is this guy naive or just stupid?)
Juan Yun: In any case, I hope you think about it some more...
Juan Yun: I will do my best to not let what we saw before happen again.
Juan Yun: Say, I haven't eaten yet... I wonder if I may have the honor of joining you?
Tindoiimu: No, we...
Juan Yun: Great, I'll tell my people to prepare. We can discuss things more as we eat~
Tingko: So, was that even a question...?
Tindoiimu: ...It's easy for him to speak about that which does not concern him.
Tindoiimu: How am I supposed to bet the fate of my entire tribe on him and his efforts?
Tingko: But, you can't destroy your relationship with him, either. After all, this is his land...
Juan Yun: Princess~ Let's have some tea before the meal. I've brought some excellent tea leaves~
Tindoiimu: *sigh* Can't hit him, can't yell at him... I seriously can't take this anymore...
Tingko: Princess! Princess!
Tindoiimu: Tingko? What's the matter? You look pale...
Tingko: I just ran into Lord Juan Yun outside. He said he had some rare snacks...
Tingko: ...and that he would bring some to you later.
Tindoiimu: Again?
Tingko: P-Princess, calm down...
Tingko: I got it! Why not sneak out and get some fresh air? When Juan Yun arrives, I'll distract him!
Tindoiimu: Um... Is that okay? Just leaving you two alone...
Tingko: If it were someone else, then maybe not. But Lord Juan Yun is harmless. He'll probably just chat my ear off.
Tindoiimu: But...
Tingko: The security guard out back should be taking a nap right about now.
Tingko: I've got this~ Hurry up and get out of here!
Tingko: Or you could stay here and enjoy some tea~
Tindoiimu: Well, then... I'll be going.
Tindoiimu: Thank you. Don't know what I'd do without you.
Tingko: It's nothing. We've grown up together. I'm your faithful servant.
Tindoiimu: (I'm not usually able to travel this far without supervision...)
Tindoiimu: (Good thing Tingko noticed that the guard takes afternoon naps...)
Tindoiimu: (Such beautiful sights. No wonder Jiyanama wanted to tell her son all about them...)
Tindoiimu: (She must be... devastated...)
Tindoiimu: It's been a long time since we've sparred like this. I miss those days.
Jihasaha: Hello again, princess.
Jihasaha: ...I'm relieved to see that you look well.
Tindoiimu: It's been so long. You're looking more and more like a soldier.
Jihasaha: And yet I still salute the princess, and the princess only.
Tindoiimu: Still the same as ever.
Tindoiimu: With your skillset, I'm sorry I just use you as my personal mailman... It's disrespectful.
Jihasaha: But I love being your personal mailman—it gives me a reason to come see you.
Jihasaha: This is the most recent letter from the king and queen. Princess, please have a look.
Tindoiimu: .........
